the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lusignan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Andre, Francois, Lucien, Marcel.","French: habitational name from Lusignan, a place in Vienne. This surname is very rare in France. Compare   Zeno  .","History: Jean Miel (or Amiel) <i>dit</i> Lusignan from Lusignan in Vienne, France, married Marie-Thérèse Latouche in Boucherville, QC, in 1699. — A French family called <i>(de) Lusignan</i> became enormously powerful in the eastern Mediterranean during the Middle Ages. Guy de Lusignan (1129–94) was king of Cyprus from 1192 to 1194 (and before that, by right of marriage, king of the crusader state of Jerusalem). Hugues de Lusignan was king of Cyprus from 1267 to 1284 and king of Jerusalem from 1268 to 1284. During the 14th century, Lusignans became kings of the Armenian kingdom of Cilicia (on the Mediterranean coast of what is now Turkey, facing Cyprus)."],"variants":[{"name":"Zeno","meanings":["Italian (mainly southern Italy), Hispanic (mainly Puerto Rico), and African American: from the personal name <i>Zeno</i>, classical Greek <i>Zēnōn</i>, a derivative of <i>Zeus</i>, the name of the king of the gods in Greek mythology. <i>Zeno</i> or <i>Zenone</i> is the name of a 4th-century Italian saint from Verona. As an African American name it was probably adopted in honor of the Stoic philosopher Zeno of Kition.","Altered form of French   Lusignan  ."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Marie de Lusignan was born about 1176, in Lusignan, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France. She married Sir Alphonse De Bryan Brienne Crusader Knight KT in 1194, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 1 October 1260, in Melle, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France, at the age of 85, and was buried in Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France."},"et":{"about 1176–October 1, 1260":"umbes 1176–1. oktoober 1260","1227–1270":"1227–1270","1176–1230":"1176–1230","1202–1252":"1202–1252","–Male":"Surnud","1176–1260":"1176–1260","01 JUN 1230":"1. juuni 1230","October 1, 1260":"1. oktoober 1260","01 Jun 1252":"1. juuni 1252","1176":"1176","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1194":"1194","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","ABT 1250":"umbes 1250","1227":"1227","1202":"1202","about 1176":"umbes 1176","Abadía de Foucarmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Francia":"Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Lusignan, 86139, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Lusignan, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Wales":"Wales","Melle, 79174, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Melle, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Walwyans Castle, Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1176–October 1, 1260":"noin 1176–1. lokakuuta 1260","1227–1270":"1227–1270","1176–1230":"1176–1230","1202–1252":"1202–1252","–Male":"Kuollut","1176–1260":"1176–1260","01 JUN 1230":"1. kesäkuuta 1230","October 1, 1260":"1. lokakuuta 1260","01 Jun 1252":"1. kesäkuuta 1252","1176":"1176","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1194":"1194","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","ABT 1250":"noin 1250","1227":"1227","1202":"1202","about 1176":"noin 1176","Abadía de Foucarmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Francia":"Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Ranska","Lusignan, 86139, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Lusigna